    "text": "The translation problem arises only when an agent must form plans from memory traces while both partial observability and overwritable world states are present.",
    "topic": "necessary conditions for memory-to-plan translation"
  },
  {
    "text": "Agents that use reactive policies or belief-state controllers without explicit planning do not encounter a memory-to-plan translation step, even under partial observability.",
    "topic": "reactive vs. planning agents"
  },
  {
    "text": "Overwritable world states, not partial observability in isolation, introduce the requirement to transform latent memory into actionable plans, because planning must account for dynamic external changes not reflected in stable internal beliefs.",
    "topic": "role of overwritable states"
  }
]
